It&#x27;s not magic -- it&#x27;s some form of crude error.<p>So first off what this does is, it expands to the expression:<p><pre><code>    &#x27;-o /dev/null&#x27; &#x27;-o /dev/null &#x27;
</code></pre>
Even if we remove the latter space by just using `{,}` instead of `{,\ }` curl still returns for me an error code 23 -- CURLE_WRITE_ERROR.<p>curl seems to interpret `&#x27;-o /wtf&#x27;` as a command to write to the file ` /wtf`, so this only makes sense if you have a directory called ` ` in the folder you&#x27;re running from.<p>You can therefore do this correctly with:<p><pre><code>    -o/dev/null{,}
</code></pre>
and that correctly writes the contents to /dev/null without issuing a curl write error.
